The Supreme Court has proven less courageous than Madison had hoped, having neither the purse nor the sword.
So even without Roosevelt’s court-packing legislation, the Supreme Court accommodated the New Deal in West Coast Hotel v. Parrish (1937).
At present, it holds the Supreme Court in higher regard than either the presidency or Congress.
Democrats are losing the Supreme Court because their ideas are unpopular, not because of the number of justices.
Should they prevail with the public, the Supreme Court won’t be far behind.